==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sled
<hw>Sled</hw> <pr>(sl⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D.
<ets>slede</ets>, G. <ets>schlitten</ets>, OHG. <ets>slito</ets>, Icel.
<ets>sle⟦edh⟧i</ets>, Sw. <ets>sl⟦aum⟧de</ets>, Dan.
<ets>sl⟦ae⟧de</ets>, and E. <ets>slide</ets>, v. See <er>Slide</er>, and
cf. <er>Sledge</er> a vehicle, <er>Sleigh</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A vehicle on runners, used for conveying loads over the snow or
ice; -- in England called <altname>sledge</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small, light vehicle with runners, used, mostly by
young persons, for sliding on snow or ice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sled</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sled
<hw>Sled</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sledded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sledding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To convey or transport on a
sled; <as>as, to <ex>sled</ex> wood or timber</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sledding</ent>⟦br⟧
